33	2020-05-06 09:33:39.541963+00	2020-05-06 10:07:24.575+00	\N	\N	\N	t	{10,4,5,6,8}	{109,130,78,56,59,61}	\N	\N	\N	\N	{362084fd-8c22-4ff3-9802-0109899bdeea}	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Reading Room: From North Sea to Red Sea	\N	<p>The North Sea to Red Sea trajectory departs from the peatlands of Scotland, traversing the continental shelf of the North Sea and the Netherlands, the trajectory cuts through the Alpine glaciers, the Po Valley, Venice and its lagoon, and beyond the Adriatic, ultimately reaching the Nile Delta, the Suez Canal and down the Red Sea, until the Gulf of Aden. The coasts of the European peninsula are being rapidly modified, with new intensified circulations of people, goods, and energy. These transformations reverberate across a wide area beyond Europe, and articulate a new set of relations, which in turn are affecting the material spaces of the region.</p><p>The trajectory takes the city of Venice and its lagoon as a conceptual starting point and draws inspiration from the maritime based polity of Venetian Republic, where the seas were the major focus of political drives and human activities. The entire Venice lagoon is a manmade ecosystem produced by a polity that decided not to move, and to reorganize the surrounding environment by creating more and more interaction with water that allowed to maintain sea level for almost 1000 years. The trajectory advocates for the development of a long-standing polity that will guide the process along the conditions. However, Venice stands both an example and a warning: the complex polity that supported the rich environments of the man-made lagoon has developed in the last hundred years into a disjoined set of elements, distancing the city from its waters.</p>	Courtesy of Territorial Agency and TBA21–Academy	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Other	\N	1	0	1	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
27	2020-04-23 21:53:28.337957+00	2020-04-27 07:31:09.85+00	\N	\N	\N	t	{10,23,42,34}	{62,106}	\N	\N	\N	\N	{362084fd-8c22-4ff3-9802-0109899bdeea}	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Coastal Urbanization	\N	<p></p><p>A collection of material related to the <a href="https://staging.ocean-archive.org/collection/25">Anthropogenic Driver</a> of Coastal Urbanization:</p><p>The convergence of urbanization and climate escalation has led to the formation of what scholar Ashley Dawson named “the prototypical social form of our age: the extreme city”, modelled after non-adaptive Eurocentric urbanist visions. The extreme city is an urban space marked by economic inequality and great unsustainability, pressured by water shortages, air pollution, heat waves, traffic chokes, sea level rise, ecological degradation and many other anthropogenic stressors. While some cities are better equipped and financially in the fortuitous position to possibly adopt preventive and mitigating measures, the top ten candidates are evenly distributed between developed and developing countries. Indeed, as Dawson argues, “how a city copes with stratifications of race, class, and gender (..) has everything to do with how well it will weather the storms that are bearing down on humanity.”Indeed the extreme city–not only in the global South–is where struggles will begin, especially in the rapidly urbanized coastal zones.</p><p>The Oceans in Transformation trajectories reveal that most major cities are located by the sea and many in low-level coastal zones. Coastal zones have experienced massive urban expansion in recent decades and are most prone to climate-related urban vulnerability. Asia’s unprecedented growth, with its urban population expected to reach 2.4 billion in 2030 is heavily at risk, with China, India, Bangladesh, Indonesia and Vietnam currently at most risk of severe marine dangers. However, Africa is expected to experience the highest rates of population growth and migration to mega-delta cities in the coastal zone, particularly in Egypt and sub-Saharan countries in Western and Eastern Africa. These countries are also characterised by very large extents of non-urban settlements in the low-lying coast areas.</p>	Courtesy of Territorial Agency and TBA21–Academy	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Area of research	\N	1	0	1	\N	https://staging.ocean-archive.org/collection/25	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	f	f
