93	private/eu-central-1:b05ef52f-57c8-4b16-a247-d657b1b03586/362084fd-8c22-4ff3-9802-0109899bdeea/21dcf7a0-85ac-11ea-9f77-0141d304c169-Screenshot 2020-04-23 at 19.03.18.png	39063cbe45ba9c7ffe47ab85e4e7089a10d0590ba3ad541d20722ebe7aab92178a5bf6eaba4ecaf61d7ecaffbac71527d520803e604f4d563fa88b68e26032bf	{}	{"rekognition_labels": [{"Name": "Outdoors", "Parents": [], "Instances": [], "Confidence": 96.6063461303711}, {"Name": "Nature", "Parents": [], "Instances": [], "Confidence": 96.6063461303711}, {"Name": "Landscape", "Parents": [{"Name": "Outdoors"}, {"Name": "Nature"}], "Instances": [], "Confidence": 96.6063461303711}, {"Name": "Scenery", "Parents": [{"Name": "Outdoors"}, {"Name": "Nature"}], "Instances": [], "Confidence": 95.32162475585938}, {"Name": "Rug", "Parents": [], "Instances": [{"Confidence": 72.98095703125, "BoundingBox": {"Top": 0.05758781358599663, "Left": 0.03776056319475174, "Width": 0.899849534034729, "Height": 0.9417880177497864}}], "Confidence": 72.98095703125}, {"Name": "Aerial View", "Parents": [{"Name": "Scenery"}, {"Name": "Outdoors"}, {"Name": "Nature"}, {"Name": "Landscape"}], "Instances": [], "Confidence": 66.6619873046875}, {"Name": "Water", "Parents": [], "Instances": [], "Confidence": 66.23408508300781}, {"Name": "Sand", "Parents": [{"Name": "Outdoors"}, {"Name": "Nature"}], "Instances": [], "Confidence": 64.50774383544922}, {"Name": "Soil", "Parents": [], "Instances": [], "Confidence": 62.14324951171875}]}	8c7b5359aa7bda0b3b6011fffd8bee94	0006100d0ff73fff9ffde2dcf18010606c3b1f19c518e730e798fbd8e4a0b0c0	2020-04-23 21:51:34.101297+00	2020-05-14 09:17:54.997+00	\N	t	{4,6,8,10}	{93,94,108,133}	\N	{ATLANTIC,INDIAN}	Image	Other	\N	362084fd-8c22-4ff3-9802-0109899bdeea	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	2020	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Dossier: World-System analysis and Earth-System theory	\N	\N	<p>The choice of the geographical areas covered by this trajectory is rooted in Immanuel Wallerstein’s World-System analysis<sup>1</sup> and Fernand Braudel’s account of the Mediterranean through the concept of the <em>longue durée</em> — the long-term historical relations that birthed Capitalism — and the role of geoecological regions in the formation of these dynamics. For Braudel, geography and climatic conditions play a fundamental role in the formation of civilizations and the sea stands as “the best witness to the Mediterranean’s age-old past”.<sup>2</sup> If biogeochemical cycles are in the foreground of the history of the region, what consequences arise when these cycles and the oceanic hydrosphere start shifting into new anthropogenic conditions? What are the speculations and the resulting conflations of issues and urgencies that are reorganizing today’s Mediterranean and the polities connected to it?<sup>3</sup></p><p>To address the fundamental questions of what “drives” the accelerated, unpredictable and unregulated transformation of the world oceans, the multiple trajectories of OiT strongly lean on Earth-System theory, developed by James Lovelock and Lynn Margulis. The Gaia theory, as they named their hypothesis, depicts the earth as synergistic and self-regulating system that created and perpetuates the conditions for life on the planet. The underlying idea of a responsive cohesion between organic existence and inorganic matter propositions a new form of organization of life. Rather than segregating and partitioning different registers of knowledge and scientific findings, the Gaia proponents (as well as Territorial Agency) argue for an aggregated understanding of sets of relations — earth, ocean, life, climate, atmosphere, inorganic chemistry, microbiology. According to Lovelock, the Earth system “is an "emergent domain" – a system that has emerged from the reciprocal evolution of organisms and their environment over the eons of life on Earth. In this system, the self-regulation of climate and chemical composition are entirely automatic. Self-regulation emerges as the system evolves.”<sup>4</sup></p><p>A human-inclusive Earth System implies that global-scale social and economic processes–the human imprint–are now becoming significant features in its functioning. When the hyper-connectivity of the human enterprise intersects with the pressures on Earth System services, concatenated global crises can propagate rapidly through the system – the fundamental proposition of the Anthropocene concept. In terms of planetary stewardship, the ocean carries the load in the functioning of the Earth System; it modulates climate variability, provides the moisture for most of rainfall and stores much more carbon than the land and atmosphere combined.</p><p>With attention to both analytical frameworks, the multiple agencies acting upon the planet as nature-cultural artefacts and forces are registered in this study as the enmeshed conditions causing the intolerable degradation of the oceans. Pivoting between world and earth science and resting on the knowledges of philosophy, the humanities, indigenous thinking and the arts, the project, according to curator Anselm Franke, “is a border operation that works at the edge of disciplinary languages, of readability, of protocols and knowledges. It has its place in the in-between of languages, at the fringe of the linguistic conventions and disciplinary universes, where lived practice and expert discourse expose their inevitable gaps.”<sup>5</sup></p><p>The North Sea to Red Sea trajectory traverses Braudelian historical centers of world-system capitalist economy, beginning with the maritime powers of the North Sea such as Antwerp, Rotterdam, Amsterdam and London, crossing Venice, and beyond the Adriatic reaching towards Cairo and the Gulf of Aden. The current transportation roads that link the North Sea to the Gulf of Aden through the Adriatic and the strait of Gibraltar reveal how these historical centers of maritime-based capitalist economies continue to be connected by the same shipping routes that structured pre-industrial economic relations. Venice occupies a central position in this analysis. It is the home of TBA21–Academy’s Ocean Space and one of the places from which this project has been conceived. Venice has been a maritime city for 1000 years and as Braudel writes, the city has been a model for the kinds of spatial organization and integration described by the trajectory: “By 1450, the itineraries of the state galleys alone, that is Venice’s official shipping, would if drawn on a map look very like an octopus, with tentacles reaching into the entire area penetrated by Italians outside the peninsula. (…) This map of the Venetian shipping routes gives a better idea than anything else could of the coordinated effort, the calculated penetration of space, and the superior command of the crucial transport sector that provided Italy for so long with its livelihood.”(6)</p><p>While offering an updated view of these dynamics, the trajectory allows anthropogenic stressors affecting the Earth System to enter the equation along with historical and social transformations: the discharge of ballast waters and the dispersal of invasive species; trawling; overfishing; oil licensing in the North Sea; chemical and conventional ammunition dumping in the Baltic, North and Celtic Seas, along the Iberian Coast and in the Mediterranean; the melting of the permafrost and glaciers of the Alps; hypoxia in the Po delta; migration emergencies arising on Europe’s borders and dispersed refugee camps and detention centers in Turkey and Greece, triggered by the EU’s security crackdown; the erosion of the Nile valley and the oil supply chain of the Red Sea. These factors all contribute directly or indirectly to the anthropogenic forcing, that marks the overall change in the Earth’s energy balance due to human (economical) activities.</p><p>Coastal digital elevation models (DEMs) that integrate ocean bathymetry and land topography are used for coastal process modelling (inundation, storm surge, sea-level rise, contaminant dispersal, etc.), ecosystems management and habitat research, coastal and marine spatial planning, hazard mitigation and community preparedness.</p><p>//</p><p><sup>1</sup> Wallerstein, Immanuel. <em>The End of the World as We Know It: Social Science for the Twenty-First Century</em> (Minneapolis: University of Minnesota Press, 1999), 192.<br><sup>2</sup> Braudel, Fernand. <em>Memory and the Mediterranean</em>, Vintage books, 2002 (originally 1998). 3 Lahoud, Adrian. “The Mediterranean: A new imaginary”. L’internationale. 2013; Lodge, A. 2010, Beyond the Frontiers. Frontex: The First Five Years, Frontex, Warsaw<br><sup>3</sup> Lovelock, James. Gaia. <em>The Practical Science of Planetary Medicine?</em>, Gaia Books Limited, 2000: 11.<br><sup>4</sup> Franke, Anselm. "Oceans in Transformation, Or: The Frontiers Of Ambiguity on the Other Side of Artistic Indeterminacy”, <em>The Commission Book</em>, Sternberg Press, 2020: 887.<br><sup>5</sup> Excerpt From: Braudel, Fernand; Reynolds, Siân. “Out of Italy”. Apple Books.</p>	\N	1	0	1	\N	\N	EN	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Exhibition Dossier	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Courtesy of TBA21–Academy	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	{2496,1602}	https://staging.ocean-archive.org/collection/28	\N	\N	\N
